/**
 * @page topic_dependencies Dependencies
 * @ingroup build
 *
 * @section dependencies_overview Overview
 *
 * ascii-chat relies on a carefully selected set of dependencies to provide its
 * real-time video chat functionality. Each dependency serves a specific purpose
 * and has been chosen for performance, security, portability, and license
 * compatibility. This page provides comprehensive documentation of all dependencies,
 * their purposes, integration methods, and configuration options.
 *
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * @section dependencies_philosophy Dependency Philosophy
 *
 * **Minimalism**: ascii-chat aims to minimize external dependencies while
 * maximizing functionality. We prefer:
 * - Native platform APIs over cross-platform libraries when viable
 * - Header-only libraries that integrate cleanly
 * - Well-maintained, battle-tested libraries with clear licenses
 * - Static linking where possible for simplified deployment
 *
 * **Security**: All dependencies are carefully vetted for:
 * - Active maintenance and security updates
 * - Clear vulnerability disclosure processes
 * - Minimal attack surface
 * - Cryptographically secure implementations where applicable
 *
 * **Performance**: Dependencies are selected for:
 * - Real-time performance characteristics
 * - Low latency and high throughput
 * - Efficient memory usage
 * - SIMD and hardware acceleration support
 *
 * @section dependencies_core Core Runtime Dependencies
 *
 * These dependencies are required for ascii-chat to function and must be
 * available at both compile time and runtime.
 *
 * @subsection dependencies_portaudio PortAudio - Cross-Platform Audio I/O
 *
 * **Purpose**: Real-time audio capture and playback for multi-client audio streaming
 *
 * **Website**: http://www.portaudio.com/
 *
 * **License**: MIT License
 *
 * **Version**: 19.7.0 or later
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Cross-platform audio I/O abstraction (Windows WASAPI, macOS CoreAudio, Linux ALSA/PulseAudio)
 * - Low-latency streaming audio support
 * - Callback-based architecture for real-time processing
 * - Automatic sample rate conversion
 * - Device enumeration and selection
 *
 * **Usage in ascii-chat**:
 * - `lib/audio.c` - Audio capture and playback implementation
 * - `lib/mixer.c` - Multi-client audio mixing with PortAudio streams
 * - Client and server audio threads use PortAudio callbacks
 *
 * **Configuration**:
 * @code{.cmake}
 * pkg_check_modules(PORTAUDIO REQUIRED portaudio-2.0)
 * target_link_libraries(ascii-chat-audio PRIVATE ${PORTAUDIO_LIBRARIES})
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Platform Notes**:
 * - **Linux**: Uses ALSA or PulseAudio backend (auto-detected)
 * - **macOS**: Uses CoreAudio backend (native)
 * - **Windows**: Uses WASAPI backend (Windows Audio Session API)
 *
 * **Performance Characteristics**:
 * - Latency: ~5-20ms (hardware dependent)
 * - Sample Rate: 48000 Hz (configurable)
 * - Buffer Size: 256-1024 samples (configurable)
 * - Channels: Mono input, stereo output
 *
 * @subsection dependencies_libsodium libsodium - Modern Cryptographic Library
 *
 * **Purpose**: End-to-end encryption, authentication, and key management
 *
 * **Website**: https://libsodium.org/
 *
 * **License**: ISC License (permissive, GPL-compatible)
 *
 * **Version**: 1.0.18 or later
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Modern cryptographic primitives (NaCl/libsodium)
 * - X25519 elliptic curve Diffie-Hellman key exchange
 * - Ed25519 digital signatures for authentication
 * - XSalsa20-Poly1305 authenticated encryption (AEAD)
 * - Constant-time operations to prevent timing attacks
 * - Cross-platform with hardware acceleration support
 *
 * **Usage in ascii-chat**:
 * - `lib/crypto/crypto.c` - Core cryptographic operations
 * - `lib/crypto/handshake.c` - Cryptographic handshake protocol
 * - `lib/crypto/keys/` - Key loading and management
 * - Session encryption for all client-server communication
 *
 * **Algorithms Used**:
 * - **Key Exchange**: X25519 (Curve25519 ECDH)
 * - **Encryption**: XSalsa20-Poly1305 (stream cipher + MAC)
 * - **Signatures**: Ed25519 (EdDSA on Curve25519)
 * - **Hashing**: BLAKE2b for key derivation
 *
 * **Configuration**:
 * @code{.cmake}
 * pkg_check_modules(LIBSODIUM REQUIRED libsodium)
 * target_link_libraries(ascii-chat-crypto PRIVATE ${LIBSODIUM_LIBRARIES})
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Security Properties**:
 * - Forward secrecy through ephemeral key exchange
 * - Authenticated encryption prevents tampering
 * - Mutual authentication with Ed25519 signatures
 * - Constant-time operations prevent timing side-channels
 *
 * @subsection dependencies_zstd zstd - Fast Compression Library
 *
 * **Purpose**: Real-time video frame compression for bandwidth reduction
 *
 * **Website**: https://facebook.github.io/zstd/
 *
 * **License**: BSD License or GPLv2 (dual licensed)
 *
 * **Version**: 1.4.0 or later
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Extremely fast compression/decompression (>400 MB/s)
 * - Configurable compression levels (1-22)
 * - Dictionary support for improved compression
 * - Streaming API for continuous data
 * - Small memory footprint
 *
 * **Usage in ascii-chat**:
 * - `lib/compression.c` - Frame compression implementation
 * - Compresses ASCII frames before network transmission
 * - Uses compression level 1 for real-time performance
 *
 * **Configuration**:
 * @code{.cmake}
 * pkg_check_modules(ZSTD REQUIRED libzstd)
 * target_link_libraries(ascii-chat-network PRIVATE ${ZSTD_LIBRARIES})
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Performance Characteristics**:
 * - Compression Level: 1 (fastest, ~50% compression ratio)
 * - Compression Speed: 400-600 MB/s (single thread)
 * - Decompression Speed: 1000-1500 MB/s (single thread)
 * - Memory Usage: ~256 KB per stream
 *
 * **Trade-offs**:
 * - Level 1 prioritizes speed over compression ratio
 * - Perfect for real-time video where latency matters
 * - Higher levels (3-6) could improve compression but add latency
 *
 * @section dependencies_vendored Vendored Dependencies (Git Submodules)
 *
 * These dependencies are included in the source tree as git submodules and
 * are built from source. This ensures version consistency and simplifies
 * deployment.
