 * @subsection dependencies_uthash uthash - Hash Table for C
 *
 * **Purpose**: Fast O(1) hash table lookups for client management and caching
 *
 * **Website**: https://troydhanson.github.io/uthash/
 *
 * **License**: BSD Revised License (permissive)
 *
 * **Version**: 2.3.0 (git submodule at deps/uthash)
 *
 * **Integration**: Header-only library (no compilation required)
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Macro-based hash table for C structures
 * - Multiple key types (integers, strings, arbitrary data)
 * - O(1) average-case lookup/insert/delete
 * - No dynamic memory for bookkeeping (embedded in structs)
 * - Deletion-safe iteration with HASH_ITER
 * - Support for sorting, counting, and filtering
 *
 * **Usage in ascii-chat**:
 * - `src/server/client.c` - Client ID → client_info_t lookup hash table
 * - `lib/platform/system.c` - Binary name → PATH presence cache
 * - `lib/lock_debug.c` - Lock ID → lock record hash table
 * - `lib/platform/symbols.c` - Address → symbol name cache
 *
 * **Example Integration**:
 * @code{.c}
 * // Add hash handle to structure
 * typedef struct {
 *   uint32_t client_id;      // Key field
 *   char *display_name;
 *   UT_hash_handle hh;       // Hash table bookkeeping
 * } client_info_t;
 *
 * // Hash table head pointer
 * client_info_t *clients_by_id = NULL;
 *
 * // Lookup by integer key
 * client_info_t *client = NULL;
 * HASH_FIND_INT(clients_by_id, &client_id, client);
 *
 * // Insert
 * HASH_ADD_INT(clients_by_id, client_id, new_client);
 *
 * // Delete
 * HASH_DELETE(hh, clients_by_id, client);
 *
 * // Safe iteration (allows deletion during loop)
 * client_info_t *current, *tmp;
 * HASH_ITER(hh, clients_by_id, current, tmp) {
 *   HASH_DELETE(hh, clients_by_id, current);
 *   free(current);
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Performance Characteristics**:
 * - Lookup: O(1) average, O(n) worst case
 * - Insert: O(1) average
 * - Delete: O(1)
 * - Memory: 32 bytes overhead per entry (UT_hash_handle)
 *
 * **Why uthash?**:
 * - Zero dependencies, header-only
 * - No separate allocation for hash table structure
 * - Type-safe macros prevent casting errors
 * - Widely used and battle-tested
 * - BSD license compatible with our project
 *
 * @subsection dependencies_bearssl BearSSL - Minimalist SSL/TLS Library
 *
 * **Purpose**: HTTPS client for fetching public keys from GitHub/GitLab
 *
 * **Website**: https://bearssl.org/
 *
 * **License**: MIT License
 *
 * **Version**: 0.6 (git submodule at deps/bearssl)
 *
 * **Integration**: Static library built from source
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Small code footprint (~100KB compiled)
 * - Minimal RAM usage (~20-30KB per connection)
 * - Constant-time cryptographic operations
 * - TLS 1.0, 1.1, 1.2, and 1.3 support
 * - X.509 certificate validation
 * - No dynamic memory allocation in crypto code
 *
 * **Usage in ascii-chat**:
 * - `lib/crypto/http_client.c` - HTTPS client implementation
 * - `lib/crypto/keys/https_keys.c` - Fetching GitHub/GitLab public keys
 * - System CA certificate loading for TLS verification
 *
 * **Why BearSSL over OpenSSL?**:
 * - Much smaller binary size (~100KB vs ~3MB)
 * - Simpler API for basic HTTPS operations
 * - Better security through constant-time operations
 * - Easier to audit due to smaller codebase
 * - No OpenSSL license complications
 *
 * **Configuration**:
 * @code{.cmake}
 * # BearSSL is built once and cached
 * add_custom_command(
 *   OUTPUT ${BEARSSL_LIB}
 *   COMMAND make -C deps/bearssl
 * )
 * target_link_libraries(ascii-chat-crypto PRIVATE ${BEARSSL_LIB})
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Build Optimization**:
 * - BearSSL is built once using its native Makefile
 * - Cached at `deps/bearssl/build/libbearssl.a`
 * - Reused across clean builds (3.75x faster rebuilds)
 * - Only rebuilt when bearssl submodule is updated
 *
 * @subsection dependencies_tomlc17 tomlc17 - TOML Configuration Parser
 *
 * **Purpose**: Configuration file parsing (future feature)
 *
 * **Website**: https://github.com/cktan/tomlc99
 *
 * **License**: MIT License
 *
 * **Version**: Custom fork with alignment fixes (git submodule at deps/tomlc17)
 *
 * **Integration**: Compiled as part of ascii-chat-core library
 *
 * **Key Features**:
 * - Full TOML 1.0.0 specification compliance
 * - Zero dependencies
 * - Simple C API for parsing TOML files
 * - Support for nested tables and arrays
 * - Type-safe value extraction
 *
 * **Current Status**:
 * - Integrated into build system
 * - Not yet used for configuration (future enhancement)
 * - Prepared for ~/.ascii-chat/config.toml support
 *
 * **Patch Applied**:
